{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HRCbiQXBCaj1cVb21PnXc6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Obtain pairwise comparisons between models\n     2→#'\n     3→#' @description\n     4→#'\n     5→#' Compare scores obtained by different models in a pairwise tournament. All\n     6→#' combinations of two models are compared against each other based on the\n     7→#' overlapping set of available forecasts common to both models.\n     8→#'\n     9→#' The input should be a `scores` object as produced by [score()]. Note that\n    10→#' adding additional unrelated columns can unpredictably change results, as\n    11→#' all present columns are taken into account when determining the set of\n    12→#' overlapping forecasts between two models.\n    13→#'\n    14→#' The output of the pairwise comparisons is a set of mean score ratios,\n    15→#' relative skill scores and p-values.\n    16→#'\n    17→#' \\if{html}{\n    18→#'   \\out{<div style=\"text-align: left\">}\n    19→#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}{options: style=\"width:750px;max-width:100\\%;\"}\n    20→#'   \\out{</div><p>}\n    21→#'   Illustration of the pairwise comparison process.\n    22→#'\n    23→#' }\n    24→#' \\if{latex}{\n    25→#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}\n    26→#' }\n    27→#'\n    28→#' *Mean score ratios*\n    29→#'\n    30→#' For every pair of two models, a mean score ratio is computed. This is simply\n    31→#' the mean score of the first model divided by the mean score of the second.\n    32→#' Mean score ratios are computed based on the set of overlapping forecasts\n    33→#' between the two models. That means that only scores for those targets are\n    34→#' taken into account for which both models have submitted a forecast.\n    35→#'\n    36→#' *(Scaled) Relative skill scores*\n    37→#'\n    38→#' The relative score of a model is the geometric mean of all mean score\n    39→#' ratios which involve that model.\n    40→#' If a baseline is provided, scaled relative skill scores will be calculated\n    41→#' as well. Scaled relative skill scores are simply the relative skill score of\n    42→#' a model divided by the relative skill score of the baseline model.\n    43→#'\n    44→#' *p-values*\n    45→#'\n    46→#' In addition, the function computes p-values for the comparison between two\n    47→#' models (again based on the set of overlapping forecasts). P-values can be\n    48→#' computed in two ways: based on a nonparametric Wilcoxon signed-rank test\n    49→#' (internally using [wilcox.test()] with `paired = TRUE`) or based on a\n    50→#' permutation test. The permutation test is based on the difference in mean\n    51→#' scores between two models. The default null hypothesis is that the mean score\n    52→#' difference is zero (see [permutation_test()]).\n    53→#' Adjusted p-values are computed by calling [p.adjust()] on the raw p-values.\n    54→#'\n    55→#' The code for the pairwise comparisons is inspired by an implementation by\n    56→#' Johannes Bracher.\n    57→#' The implementation of the permutation test follows the function\n    58→#' `permutationTest` from the `surveillance` package by Michael Höhle,\n    59→#' Andrea Riebler and Michaela Paul.\n    60→#'\n    61→#' @param compare Character vector with a single colum name that defines the\n    62→#'   elements for the pairwise comparison. For example, if this is set to\n    63→#'   \"model\" (the default), then elements of the \"model\" column will be\n    64→#'   compared.\n    65→#' @param by Character vector with column names that define further grouping\n    66→#'   levels for the pairwise comparisons. By default this is `NULL` and there\n    67→#'   will be one relative skill score per distinct entry of the column selected\n    68→#'   in `compare`. If further columns are given here, for example, `by =\n    69→#'   \"location\"` with `compare = \"model\"`, then one separate relative skill\n    70→#'   score is calculated for every model in every location.\n    71→#' @param metric A string with the name of the metric for which\n    72→#'   a relative skill shall be computed. By default this is either \"crps\",\n    73→#'   \"wis\" or \"brier_score\" if any of these are available.\n    74→#' @param baseline A string with the name of a model. If a baseline is\n    75→#'   given, then a scaled relative skill with respect to the baseline will be\n    76→#'   returned. By default (`NULL`), relative skill will not be scaled with\n    77→#'   respect to a baseline model.\n    78→#' @param ... Additional arguments for the comparison between two models. See\n    79→#'   [compare_forecasts()] for more information.\n    80→#' @inheritParams summarise_scores\n    81→#' @returns A data.table with the results of pairwise comparisons\n    82→#' containing the mean score ratios (`mean_scores_ratio`),\n    83→#' unadjusted (`pval`) and adjusted (`adj_pval`) p-values, and relative skill\n    84→#' values of each model (`..._relative_skill`). If a baseline model is given\n    85→#' then the scaled relative skill is reported as well\n    86→#' (`..._scaled_relative_skill`).\n    87→#' @importFrom data.table as.data.table data.table setnames copy\n    88→#' @importFrom stats sd rbinom wilcox.test p.adjust\n    89→#' @importFrom utils combn\n    90→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_subset assert_character assert_disjunct\n    91→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort cli_inform cli_warn\n    92→#' @export\n    93→#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n    94→#' @author Johannes Bracher, \\email{johannes.bracher@@kit.edu}\n    95→#' @keywords scoring\n    96→#' @examples\n    97→#' \\dontshow{\n    98→#'   data.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n    99→#' }\n   100→#'\n   101→#'\n   102→#' scores <- example_quantile |>\n   103→#'  as_forecast_quantile() |>\n   104→#'  score()\n   105→#'\n   106→#' pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(scores, by = \"target_type\")\n   107→#' pairwise2 <- get_pairwise_comparisons(\n   108→#'   scores, by = \"target_type\", baseline = \"EuroCOVIDhub-baseline\"\n   109→#' )\n   110→#'\n   111→#' library(ggplot2)\n   112→#' plot_pairwise_comparisons(pairwise, type = \"mean_scores_ratio\") +\n   113→#'   facet_wrap(~target_type)\n   114→\n   115→get_pairwise_comparisons <- function(\n   116→  scores,\n   117→  compare = \"model\",\n   118→  by = NULL,\n   119→  metric = intersect(c(\"wis\", \"crps\", \"brier_score\"), names(scores)),\n   120→  baseline = NULL,\n   121→  ...\n   122→) {\n   123→\n   124→  # input checks ---------------------------------------------------------------\n   125→  scores <- ensure_data.table(scores)\n   126→  # check that column in 'compare' is present\n   127→  assert(check_columns_present(scores, compare))\n   128→  # check that column(s) in `by` ar not in `compare`\n   129→  assert_disjunct(by, compare)\n   130→\n   131→  # we need the score names attribute to make sure we can determine the\n   132→  # forecast unit correctly, so here we check it exists\n   133→  metrics <- get_metrics.scores(scores, error = TRUE)\n   134→\n   135→  # check that metric is a subset of the scores and is of length 1\n   136→  assert_subset(metric, metrics, empty.ok = FALSE)\n   137→  assert_character(metric, len = 1)\n   138→\n   139→  # check that columns in 'by' are present\n   140→  #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   141→  if (length(by) > 0) {\n   142→    by_cols <- check_columns_present(scores, by)\n   143→    if (!isTRUE(by_cols)) {\n   144→      cli_abort(\n   145→        c(\n   146→          \"!\" = \"Not all columns specified in `by` are present: {.var {by_cols}}\"\n   147→        )\n   148→      )\n   149→      #nolint end\n   150→    }\n   151→  } else {\n   152→    ## set explicitly to character(0) in case it was given as NULL\n   153→    by <- character(0)\n   154→  }\n   155→\n   156→  # check that baseline exists\n   157→  comparators <- as.vector(unique(scores[[compare]]))\n   158→  assert_subset(baseline, comparators)\n   159→\n   160→  # check there are enough comparators\n   161→  if (length(setdiff(comparators, baseline)) < 2) {\n   162→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   163→    cli_abort(\n   164→      c(\n   165→        \"!\" = \"More than one non-baseline model is needed to compute\n   166→        pairwise compairisons.\"\n   167→      )\n   168→    )\n   169→    #nolint end\n   170→  }\n   171→\n   172→  # check that values of the chosen metric are not NA\n   173→  if (anyNA(scores[[metric]])) {\n   174→    scores <- scores[!is.na(scores[[metric]])]\n   175→    if (nrow(scores) == 0) {\n   176→      #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   177→      cli_abort(\n   178→        c(\n   179→          \"!\" = \"After removing {.val NA} values for {.var {metric}},\n   180→         no values were left.\"\n   181→        )\n   182→      )\n   183→    }\n   184→    cli_warn(\n   185→      c(\n   186→        \"!\" = \"Some values for the metric {.var {metric}}\n   187→         are NA. These have been removed.\",\n   188→        \"i\" = \"Maybe choose a different metric?\"\n   189→      )\n   190→    )\n   191→    #nolint end\n   192→  }\n   193→\n   194→  # check that all values of the chosen metric are positive\n   195→  if (any(sign(scores[[metric]]) < 0) && any(sign(scores[[metric]]) > 0)) {\n   196→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n   197→    cli_abort(\n   198→      c(\n   199→        \"!\" = \"To compute pairwise comparisons, all values of {.var {metric}}\n   200→       must have the same sign.\"\n   201→      )\n   202→    )\n   203→    #nolint end\n   204→  }\n   205→\n   206→  # identify unit of single observation.\n   207→  forecast_unit <- get_forecast_unit(scores)\n   208→\n   209→  # if compare is equal to forecast_unit, then pairwise comparisons don't make\n   210→  # sense\n   211→  # if compare == forecast_unit then all relative skill scores will simply be 1.\n   212→  if (setequal(compare, forecast_unit)) {\n   213→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   214→    cli_warn(\n   215→      c(\n   216→        \"!\" = \"`compare` is set to the unit of a single forecast. This doesn't\n   217→            look right.\",\n   218→        \"i\" = \"All relative skill scores will be equal to 1.\"\n   219→      )\n   220→    )\n   221→    #nolint end\n   222→  } else if (setequal(c(compare, by), forecast_unit)) {\n   223→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   224→    cli_inform(\n   225→      c(\n   226→        \"!\" = \"relative skill can only be computed if the combination of\n   227→        `compare` and `by` is different from the unit of a single forecast.\",\n   228→        \"i\" = \"`by` was set to an empty character vector\"\n   229→      )\n   230→    )\n   231→    #nolint end\n   232→    by <- character(0)\n   233→  }\n   234→\n   235→  # do the pairwise comparison -------------------------------------------------\n   236→  # split data set into groups determined by 'by'\n   237→  split_scores <- split(scores, by = by)\n   238→\n   239→  results <- lapply(split_scores,\n   240→    FUN = function(scores) {\n   241→      pairwise_comparison_one_group(\n   242→        scores = scores,\n   243→        metric = metric,\n   244→        baseline = baseline,\n   245→        compare = compare,\n   246→        by = by,\n   247→        ...\n   248→      )\n   249→    }\n   250→  )\n   251→\n   252→  out <- data.table::rbindlist(results)\n   253→\n   254→  return(out[])\n   255→}\n   256→\n   257→#' @title Do pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts\n   258→#'\n   259→#' @description\n   260→#' This function does the pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts, but\n   261→#' multiple models involved. It gets called from [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   262→#' [get_pairwise_comparisons()] splits the data into arbitrary subgroups\n   263→#' specified by the user (e.g. if pairwise comparison should be done separately\n   264→#' for different forecast targets) and then the actual pairwise comparison for\n   265→#' that subgroup is managed from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()]. In order to\n   266→#' actually do the comparison between two models over a subset of common\n   267→#' forecasts it calls [compare_forecasts()].\n   268→#' @inherit get_pairwise_comparisons params return\n   269→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n   270→#' @importFrom data.table setnames\n   271→#' @keywords internal\n   272→\n   273→pairwise_comparison_one_group <- function(scores,\n   274→                                          metric,\n   275→                                          baseline,\n   276→                                          compare = \"model\",\n   277→                                          by,\n   278→                                          ...) {\n   279→  if (!(compare %in% names(scores))) {\n   280→    cli_abort(\n   281→      \"pairwise comparisons require a column as given by `compare`\"\n   282→    )\n   283→  }\n   284→\n   285→  # get list of models\n   286→  comparators <- unique(scores[[compare]])\n   287→\n   288→  # if there aren't enough models to do any comparison, abort\n   289→  if (length(comparators) < 2) {\n   290→    cli_abort(\n   291→      c(\"!\" = \"There are not enough comparators to do any comparison\")\n   292→    )\n   293→  }\n   294→\n   295→  # create a data.frame with results\n   296→  # we only need to do the calculation once, because for the ratio that\n   297→  # should just be the inverse and for the permutation the result should\n   298→  # be the same\n   299→\n   300→  # set up initial data.frame with all possible pairwise comparisons\n   301→  combinations <- data.table::as.data.table(t(combn(comparators, m = 2)))\n   302→  colnames(combinations) <- c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\")\n   303→\n   304→  combinations[, c(\"ratio\", \"pval\") := compare_forecasts(\n   305→    compare = compare,\n   306→    scores = scores,\n   307→    name_comparator1 = ..compare,\n   308→    name_comparator2 = compare_against,\n   309→    metric = metric,\n   310→    ...\n   311→  ),\n   312→  by = seq_len(NROW(combinations))\n   313→  ]\n   314→\n   315→  combinations <- combinations[order(ratio)]\n   316→  combinations[, adj_pval := p.adjust(pval)]\n   317→\n   318→  # mirror computations\n   319→  combinations_mirrored <- data.table::copy(combinations)\n   320→  setnames(combinations_mirrored,\n   321→    old = c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\"),\n   322→    new = c(\"compare_against\", \"..compare\")\n   323→  )\n   324→  combinations_mirrored[, ratio := 1 / ratio]\n   325→\n   326→  # add a one for those that are the same\n   327→  combinations_equal <- data.table::data.table(\n   328→    ..compare = comparators,\n   329→    compare_against = comparators,\n   330→    ratio = 1,\n   331→    pval = 1,\n   332→    adj_pval = 1\n   333→  )\n   334→  result <- data.table::rbindlist(list(\n   335→    combinations,\n   336→    combinations_mirrored,\n   337→    combinations_equal\n   338→  ),\n   339→  use.names = TRUE\n   340→  )\n   341→\n   342→  # make result character instead of factor\n   343→  result[, `:=`(\n   344→    ..compare = as.character(..compare),\n   345→    compare_against = as.character(compare_against)\n   346→  )]\n   347→\n   348→  setnames(result, old = \"..compare\", new = compare)\n   349→\n   350→  # calculate relative skill as geometric mean\n   351→  # small theta is again better (assuming that the score is negatively oriented)\n   352→  result[, `:=`(\n   353→    theta = geometric_mean(ratio)\n   354→  ),\n   355→  by = compare,\n   356→  ]\n   357→\n   358→  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n   359→    baseline_theta <- unique(result[get(compare) == baseline, ]$theta)\n   360→    if (length(baseline_theta) == 0) {\n   361→      cli_abort(\n   362→        \"Baseline comparator {.var {baseline}} missing.\"\n   363→      )\n   364→    }\n   365→    result[, rel_to_baseline := theta / baseline_theta]\n   366→  }\n   367→\n   368→  # remove all the rows that are not present in by before merging\n   369→  cols_to_keep <- unique(c(by, compare))\n   370→  cols_to_remove <- colnames(scores)[!(colnames(scores) %in% cols_to_keep)]\n   371→  scores[, eval(cols_to_remove) := NULL]\n   372→  scores <- unique(scores)\n   373→  # allow.cartesian needs to be set as sometimes rows will be duplicated a lot\n   374→  out <- merge(scores, result, by = compare, all = TRUE)\n   375→\n   376→  # rename ratio to mean_scores_ratio\n   377→  data.table::setnames(out,\n   378→    old = c(\"ratio\", \"theta\"),\n   379→    new = c(\n   380→      \"mean_scores_ratio\",\n   381→      paste(metric, \"relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n   382→    )\n   383→  )\n   384→  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n   385→    data.table::setnames(out,\n   386→      old = \"rel_to_baseline\",\n   387→      new = paste(metric, \"scaled_relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n   388→    )\n   389→  }\n   390→\n   391→  return(out[])\n   392→}\n   393→\n   394→#' @title Compare a subset of common forecasts\n   395→#'\n   396→#' @description\n   397→#' This function compares two comparators based on the subset of forecasts for which\n   398→#' both comparators have made a prediction. It gets called\n   399→#' from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()], which handles the\n   400→#' comparison of multiple comparators on a single set of forecasts (there are no\n   401→#' subsets of forecasts to be distinguished). [pairwise_comparison_one_group()]\n   402→#' in turn gets called from from [get_pairwise_comparisons()] which can handle\n   403→#' pairwise comparisons for a set of forecasts with multiple subsets, e.g.\n   404→#' pairwise comparisons for one set of forecasts, but done separately for two\n   405→#' different forecast targets.\n   406→#' @inheritParams get_pairwise_comparisons\n   407→#' @param name_comparator1 Character, name of the first comparator\n   408→#' @param name_comparator2 Character, name of the comparator to compare against\n   409→#' @param one_sided Boolean, default is `FALSE`, whether two conduct a one-sided\n   410→#'   instead of a two-sided test to determine significance in a pairwise\n   411→#'   comparison.\n   412→#' @param test_type Character, either \"non_parametric\" (the default), \"permutation\",\n   413→#'   or NULL. This determines which kind of test shall be conducted to determine\n   414→#'   p-values. If NULL, no test will be conducted and p-values will be NA.\n   415→#' @param n_permutations Numeric, the number of permutations for a\n   416→#'   permutation test. Default is 999.\n   417→#' @returns A list with mean score ratios and p-values for the comparison\n   418→#' between two comparators\n   419→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n   420→#' @author Johannes Bracher, \\email{johannes.bracher@@kit.edu}\n   421→#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n   422→#' @keywords internal\n   423→\n   424→compare_forecasts <- function(scores,\n   425→                              compare = \"model\",\n   426→                              name_comparator1,\n   427→                              name_comparator2,\n   428→                              metric,\n   429→                              one_sided = FALSE,\n   430→                              test_type = c(\"non_parametric\", \"permutation\", NULL),\n   431→                              n_permutations = 999) {\n   432→  scores <- data.table::as.data.table(scores)\n   433→\n   434→  forecast_unit <- get_forecast_unit(scores)\n   435→\n   436→  if (!(compare %in% names(scores))) {\n   437→    cli_abort(\n   438→      \"pairwise comparisons require a column as given by `compare`\"\n   439→    )\n   440→  }\n   441→\n   442→  # select only columns in c(by, var)\n   443→  a <- scores[get(compare) == name_comparator1]\n   444→  b <- scores[get(compare) == name_comparator2]\n   445→\n   446→  # remove compare column from 'by' before merging\n   447→  merge_by <- setdiff(forecast_unit, compare)\n   448→\n   449→  overlap <- merge(a, b, by = merge_by, allow.cartesian = TRUE)\n   450→  overlap <- unique(overlap)\n   451→\n   452→  if (nrow(overlap) == 0) {\n   453→    return(list(ratio = NA_real_, pval = NA_real_))\n   454→  }\n   455→\n   456→  values_x <- overlap[[paste0(metric, \".x\")]]\n   457→  values_y <- overlap[[paste0(metric, \".y\")]]\n   458→\n   459→  # calculate ratio to of average scores achieved by both comparator.\n   460→  # this should be equivalent to theta_ij in Johannes Bracher's document.\n   461→  # ratio < 1 --> comparator 1 is better.\n   462→  # note we could also take mean(values_x) / mean(values_y), as it cancels out\n   463→  ratio <- sum(values_x) / sum(values_y)\n   464→\n   465→  # If test_type is NULL, return NA for p-value\n   466→  if (is.null(test_type)) {\n   467→    pval <- NA_real_\n   468→  } else {\n   469→    # test whether the ratio is significantly different from one\n   470→    # equivalently, one can test whether the difference between the two values\n   471→    # is significantly different from zero.\n   472→    test_type <- match.arg(test_type)\n   473→    if (test_type == \"permutation\") {\n   474→      # adapted from the surveillance package\n   475→      pval <- permutation_test(values_x, values_y,\n   476→        n_permutation = n_permutations,\n   477→        one_sided = one_sided,\n   478→        comparison_mode = \"difference\"\n   479→      )\n   480→    } else {\n   481→      # this probably needs some more thought\n   482→      # alternative: do a paired t-test on ranks?\n   483→      pval <- wilcox.test(values_x, values_y, paired = TRUE)$p.value\n   484→    }\n   485→  }\n   486→\n   487→  return(list(\n   488→    mean_scores_ratio = ratio,\n   489→    pval = pval\n   490→  ))\n   491→}\n   492→\n   493→\n   494→#' @title Calculate geometric mean\n   495→#'\n   496→#' @details\n   497→#' Used in [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   498→#'\n   499→#' @param x Numeric vector of values for which to calculate the geometric mean.\n   500→#' @returns The geometric mean of the values in `x`. `NA` values are ignored.\n   501→#'\n   502→#' @keywords internal\n   503→geometric_mean <- function(x) {\n   504→  geometric_mean <- exp(mean(log(x[!is.na(x)])))\n   505→  return(geometric_mean)\n   506→}\n   507→\n   508→#' @title Simple permutation test\n   509→#'\n   510→#' @description\n   511→#' The implementation of the permutation test follows the\n   512→#' function\n   513→#' `permutationTest` from the `surveillance` package by Michael Höhle,\n   514→#' Andrea Riebler and Michaela Paul.\n   515→#' The function compares two vectors of scores. It computes the mean of each\n   516→#' vector independently and then takes either the difference or the ratio of\n   517→#' the two. This observed difference or ratio is compared against the same\n   518→#' test statistic based on permutations of the original data.\n   519→#'\n   520→#' Used in [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   521→#'\n   522→#' @param scores1 Vector of scores to compare against another vector of scores.\n   523→#' @param scores2 A second vector of scores to compare against the first\n   524→#' @param n_permutation The number of replications to use for a permutation\n   525→#' test. More replications yield more exact results, but require more\n   526→#' computation.\n   527→#' @param one_sided Whether or not to compute a one-sided test. Default is\n   528→#'   `FALSE`.\n   529→#' @param comparison_mode How to compute the test statistic for the comparison\n   530→#'   of the two scores. Should be either \"difference\" or \"ratio\".\n   531→#'\n   532→#' @returns p-value of the permutation test\n   533→#' @keywords internal\n   534→permutation_test <- function(scores1,\n   535→                             scores2,\n   536→                             n_permutation = 999,\n   537→                             one_sided = FALSE,\n   538→                             comparison_mode = c(\"difference\", \"ratio\")) {\n   539→  nTime <- length(scores1)\n   540→  meanscores1 <- mean(scores1)\n   541→  meanscores2 <- mean(scores2)\n   542→  comparison_mode <- match.arg(comparison_mode)\n   543→  if (comparison_mode == \"ratio\") {\n   544→    # distinguish between on-sided and two-sided:\n   545→    test_stat_observed <- ifelse(\n   546→      one_sided,\n   547→      meanscores1 / meanscores2,\n   548→      max(meanscores1 / meanscores2, meanscores2 / meanscores1)\n   549→    )\n   550→  } else {\n   551→    test_stat_observed <- ifelse(\n   552→      one_sided,\n   553→      meanscores1 - meanscores2,\n   554→      abs(meanscores1 - meanscores2)\n   555→    )\n   556→  }\n   557→  test_stat_permuted <- replicate(n_permutation, {\n   558→    sel <- rbinom(nTime, size = 1, prob = 0.5)\n   559→    g1 <- (sum(scores1[sel == 0]) + sum(scores2[sel == 1])) / nTime\n   560→    g2 <- (sum(scores1[sel == 1]) + sum(scores2[sel == 0])) / nTime\n   561→    if (comparison_mode == \"ratio\") {\n   562→      ifelse(one_sided, g1 / g2, max(g1 / g2, g2 / g1))\n   563→    } else {\n   564→      ifelse(one_sided, g1 - g2, abs(g1 - g2))\n   565→    }\n   566→  })\n   567→  pVal <- (1 + sum(test_stat_permuted >= test_stat_observed)) / (n_permutation + 1)\n   568→  # plus ones to make sure p-val is never 0?\n   569→  return(pVal)\n   570→}\n   571→\n   572→\n   573→#' Add relative skill scores based on pairwise comparisons\n   574→#'\n   575→#' Adds a columns with relative skills computed by running\n   576→#' pairwise comparisons on the scores.\n   577→#' For more information on\n   578→#' the computation of relative skill, see [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   579→#' Relative skill will be calculated for the aggregation level specified in\n   580→#' `by`.\n   581→#'\n   582→#' @inheritParams get_pairwise_comparisons\n   583→#' @export\n   584→#' @keywords scoring\n   585→add_relative_skill <- function(\n   586→  scores,\n   587→  compare = \"model\",\n   588→  by = NULL,\n   589→  metric = intersect(c(\"wis\", \"crps\", \"brier_score\"), names(scores)),\n   590→  baseline = NULL,\n   591→  ...\n   592→) {\n   593→\n   594→  # input checks are done in `get_pairwise_comparisons()`\n   595→  # do pairwise comparisons ----------------------------------------------------\n   596→  pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(\n   597→    scores = scores,\n   598→    metric = metric,\n   599→    baseline = baseline,\n   600→    compare = compare,\n   601→    by = by,\n   602→    ...\n   603→  )\n   604→\n   605→  # store original metrics\n   606→  metrics <- get_metrics.scores(scores)\n   607→\n   608→  # delete unnecessary columns\n   609→  pairwise[, c(\n   610→    \"compare_against\", \"mean_scores_ratio\",\n   611→    \"pval\", \"adj_pval\"\n   612→  ) := NULL]\n   613→  pairwise <- unique(pairwise)\n   614→\n   615→  # merge back\n   616→  scores <- merge(\n   617→    scores, pairwise, all.x = TRUE, by = get_forecast_unit(pairwise)\n   618→  )\n   619→\n   620→  # Update score names\n   621→  new_metrics <- paste(\n   622→    metric, c(\"relative_skill\", \"scaled_relative_skill\"),\n   623→    sep = \"_\"\n   624→  )\n   625→  new_metrics <- new_metrics[new_metrics %in% names(scores)]\n   626→  scores <- new_scores(scores, metrics = c(metrics, new_metrics))\n   627→\n   628→  return(scores)\n   629→}\n   630→\n   631→\n   632→#' @title Plot heatmap of pairwise comparisons\n   633→#'\n   634→#' @description\n   635→#' Creates a heatmap of the ratios or pvalues from a pairwise comparison\n   636→#' between models.\n   637→#'\n   638→#' @param comparison_result A data.frame as produced by\n   639→#' [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n   640→#' @param type Character vector of length one that is either\n   641→#'   \"mean_scores_ratio\" or \"pval\". This denotes whether to\n   642→#'   visualise the ratio or the p-value of the pairwise comparison.\n   643→#'   Default is \"mean_scores_ratio\".\n   644→#' @importFrom ggplot2 ggplot aes geom_tile geom_text labs coord_cartesian\n   645→#'   scale_fill_gradient2 theme_light element_text\n   646→#' @importFrom data.table as.data.table setnames rbindlist\n   647→#' @importFrom stats reorder\n   648→#' @importFrom ggplot2 labs coord_cartesian facet_wrap facet_grid theme\n   649→#'   element_text element_blank\n   650→#' @return\n   651→#' A ggplot object with a heatmap of mean score ratios from pairwise\n   652→#' comparisons.\n   653→#' @export\n   654→#' @examples\n   655→#' library(ggplot2)\n   656→#' scores <- example_quantile |>\n   657→#'   as_forecast_quantile() |>\n   658→#'   score()\n   659→#' pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(scores, by = \"target_type\")\n   660→#' plot_pairwise_comparisons(pairwise, type = \"mean_scores_ratio\") +\n   661→#'   facet_wrap(~target_type)\n   662→\n   663→plot_pairwise_comparisons <- function(comparison_result,\n   664→                                      type = c(\"mean_scores_ratio\", \"pval\")) {\n   665→  comparison_result <- ensure_data.table(comparison_result)\n   666→  type <- match.arg(type)\n   667→\n   668→  relative_skill_metric <- grep(\n   669→    \"(?<!scaled)_relative_skill$\", colnames(comparison_result),\n   670→    value = TRUE, perl = TRUE\n   671→  )\n   672→  comparison_result[, model := reorder(model, -get(relative_skill_metric))]\n   673→  levels <- levels(comparison_result$model)\n   674→\n   675→  get_fill_scale <- function(values, breaks, plot_scales) {\n   676→    values[is.na(values)] <- 1 # this would be either ratio = 1 or pval = 1\n   677→    scale <- cut(\n   678→      values,\n   679→      breaks = breaks,\n   680→      include.lowest = TRUE,\n   681→      right = FALSE,\n   682→      labels = plot_scales\n   683→    )\n   684→    return(as.numeric(as.character(scale)))\n   685→  }\n   686→\n   687→  type <- match.arg(type)\n   688→\n   689→  if (type == \"mean_scores_ratio\") {\n   690→    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := round(mean_scores_ratio, 2)]\n   691→\n   692→    # implement breaks for colour heatmap\n   693→    breaks <- c(0, 0.1, 0.5, 0.75, 1, 1.33, 2, 10, Inf)\n   694→    plot_scales <- c(-1, -0.5, -0.25, 0, 0, 0.25, 0.5, 1)\n   695→    comparison_result[, fill_col := get_fill_scale(\n   696→      var_of_interest,\n   697→      breaks, plot_scales\n   698→    )]\n   699→\n   700→    high_col <- \"salmon\"\n   701→  } else if (type == \"pval\") {\n   702→    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := round(pval, 3)]\n   703→    # implemnt breaks for colour heatmap\n   704→    breaks <- c(0, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1)\n   705→    plot_scales <- c(1, 0.5, 0.1, 0)\n   706→    comparison_result[, fill_col := get_fill_scale(\n   707→      var_of_interest,\n   708→      breaks, plot_scales\n   709→    )]\n   710→\n   711→    high_col <- \"palegreen3\"\n   712→    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := as.character(var_of_interest)]\n   713→    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := ifelse(var_of_interest == \"0\",\n   714→                                                  \"< 0.001\", var_of_interest)]\n   715→  }\n   716→\n   717→  plot <- ggplot(\n   718→    comparison_result,\n   719→    aes(\n   720→      y = reorder(model, 1 / mean_scores_ratio, FUN = geometric_mean),\n   721→      x = reorder(compare_against, mean_scores_ratio, FUN = geometric_mean),\n   722→      fill = fill_col\n   723→    )\n   724→  ) +\n   725→    geom_tile(\n   726→      color = \"white\",\n   727→      width = 0.97, height = 0.97\n   728→    ) +\n   729→    geom_text(aes(label = var_of_interest),\n   730→              na.rm = TRUE) +\n   731→    scale_fill_gradient2(\n   732→      low = \"steelblue\", mid = \"grey95\",\n   733→      high = high_col,\n   734→      na.value = \"lightgrey\",\n   735→      midpoint = 0,\n   736→      limits = c(-1, 1),\n   737→      name = NULL\n   738→    ) +\n   739→    theme_scoringutils() +\n   740→    theme(\n   741→      axis.text.x = element_text(\n   742→        angle = 90, vjust = 1,\n   743→        hjust = 1\n   744→      ),\n   745→      legend.position = \"none\"\n   746→    ) +\n   747→    labs(\n   748→      x = \"\", y = \"\"\n   749→    ) +\n   750→    coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE)\n   751→  if (type == \"mean_scores_ratio\") {\n   752→    plot <- plot +\n   753→      theme(\n   754→        axis.text.x = element_text(\n   755→          angle = 90, vjust = 1,\n   756→          hjust = 1, color = \"brown4\"\n   757→        ),\n   758→        axis.text.y = element_text(color = \"steelblue4\")\n   759→      )\n   760→  }\n   761→\n   762→  return(plot)\n   763→}\n   764→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1ac3f64f-dcb6-4522-9adc-54c9604569be","uuid":"ab350e54-336c-4327-95c9-6aca706091fc","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/nikos/github-synced/scoringutils-pipeline/R/pairwise-comparisons.R","content":"#' @title Obtain pairwise comparisons between models\n#'\n#' @description\n#'\n#' Compare scores obtained by different models in a pairwise tournament. All\n#' combinations of two models are compared against each other based on the\n#' overlapping set of available forecasts common to both models.\n#'\n#' The input should be a `scores` object as produced by [score()]. Note that\n#' adding additional unrelated columns can unpredictably change results, as\n#' all present columns are taken into account when determining the set of\n#' overlapping forecasts between two models.\n#'\n#' The output of the pairwise comparisons is a set of mean score ratios,\n#' relative skill scores and p-values.\n#'\n#' \\if{html}{\n#'   \\out{<div style=\"text-align: left\">}\n#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}{options: style=\"width:750px;max-width:100\\%;\"}\n#'   \\out{</div><p>}\n#'   Illustration of the pairwise comparison process.\n#'\n#' }\n#' \\if{latex}{\n#'   \\figure{pairwise-illustration.png}\n#' }\n#'\n#' *Mean score ratios*\n#'\n#' For every pair of two models, a mean score ratio is computed. This is simply\n#' the mean score of the first model divided by the mean score of the second.\n#' Mean score ratios are computed based on the set of overlapping forecasts\n#' between the two models. That means that only scores for those targets are\n#' taken into account for which both models have submitted a forecast.\n#'\n#' *(Scaled) Relative skill scores*\n#'\n#' The relative score of a model is the geometric mean of all mean score\n#' ratios which involve that model.\n#' If a baseline is provided, scaled relative skill scores will be calculated\n#' as well. Scaled relative skill scores are simply the relative skill score of\n#' a model divided by the relative skill score of the baseline model.\n#'\n#' *p-values*\n#'\n#' In addition, the function computes p-values for the comparison between two\n#' models (again based on the set of overlapping forecasts). P-values can be\n#' computed in two ways: based on a nonparametric Wilcoxon signed-rank test\n#' (internally using [wilcox.test()] with `paired = TRUE`) or based on a\n#' permutation test. The permutation test is based on the difference in mean\n#' scores between two models. The default null hypothesis is that the mean score\n#' difference is zero (see [permutation_test()]).\n#' Adjusted p-values are computed by calling [p.adjust()] on the raw p-values.\n#'\n#' The code for the pairwise comparisons is inspired by an implementation by\n#' Johannes Bracher.\n#' The implementation of the permutation test follows the function\n#' `permutationTest` from the `surveillance` package by Michael Höhle,\n#' Andrea Riebler and Michaela Paul.\n#'\n#' @param compare Character vector with a single colum name that defines the\n#'   elements for the pairwise comparison. For example, if this is set to\n#'   \"model\" (the default), then elements of the \"model\" column will be\n#'   compared.\n#' @param by Character vector with column names that define further grouping\n#'   levels for the pairwise comparisons. By default this is `NULL` and there\n#'   will be one relative skill score per distinct entry of the column selected\n#'   in `compare`. If further columns are given here, for example, `by =\n#'   \"location\"` with `compare = \"model\"`, then one separate relative skill\n#'   score is calculated for every model in every location.\n#' @param metric A string with the name of the metric for which\n#'   a relative skill shall be computed. By default this is either \"crps\",\n#'   \"wis\" or \"brier_score\" if any of these are available.\n#' @param baseline A string with the name of a model. If a baseline is\n#'   given, then a scaled relative skill with respect to the baseline will be\n#'   returned. By default (`NULL`), relative skill will not be scaled with\n#'   respect to a baseline model.\n#' @param ... Additional arguments for the comparison between two models. See\n#'   [compare_forecasts()] for more information.\n#' @inheritParams summarise_scores\n#' @returns A data.table with the results of pairwise comparisons\n#' containing the mean score ratios (`mean_scores_ratio`),\n#' unadjusted (`pval`) and adjusted (`adj_pval`) p-values, and relative skill\n#' values of each model (`..._relative_skill`). If a baseline model is given\n#' then the scaled relative skill is reported as well\n#' (`..._scaled_relative_skill`).\n#' @importFrom data.table as.data.table data.table setnames copy\n#' @importFrom stats sd rbinom wilcox.test p.adjust\n#' @importFrom utils combn\n#' @importFrom checkmate assert_subset assert_character assert_disjunct\n#' @importFrom cli cli_abort cli_inform cli_warn\n#' @export\n#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n#' @author Johannes Bracher, \\email{johannes.bracher@@kit.edu}\n#' @keywords scoring\n#' @examples\n#' \\dontshow{\n#'   data.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n#' }\n#'\n#'\n#' scores <- example_quantile |>\n#'  as_forecast_quantile() |>\n#'  score()\n#'\n#' pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(scores, by = \"target_type\")\n#' pairwise2 <- get_pairwise_comparisons(\n#'   scores, by = \"target_type\", baseline = \"EuroCOVIDhub-baseline\"\n#' )\n#'\n#' library(ggplot2)\n#' plot_pairwise_comparisons(pairwise, type = \"mean_scores_ratio\") +\n#'   facet_wrap(~target_type)\n\nget_pairwise_comparisons <- function(\n  scores,\n  compare = \"model\",\n  by = NULL,\n  metric = intersect(c(\"wis\", \"crps\", \"brier_score\"), names(scores)),\n  baseline = NULL,\n  ...\n) {\n\n  # input checks ---------------------------------------------------------------\n  scores <- ensure_data.table(scores)\n  # check that column in 'compare' is present\n  assert(check_columns_present(scores, compare))\n  # check that column(s) in `by` ar not in `compare`\n  assert_disjunct(by, compare)\n\n  # we need the score names attribute to make sure we can determine the\n  # forecast unit correctly, so here we check it exists\n  metrics <- get_metrics.scores(scores, error = TRUE)\n\n  # check that metric is a subset of the scores and is of length 1\n  assert_subset(metric, metrics, empty.ok = FALSE)\n  assert_character(metric, len = 1)\n\n  # check that columns in 'by' are present\n  #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n  if (length(by) > 0) {\n    by_cols <- check_columns_present(scores, by)\n    if (!isTRUE(by_cols)) {\n      cli_abort(\n        c(\n          \"!\" = \"Not all columns specified in `by` are present: {.var {by_cols}}\"\n        )\n      )\n      #nolint end\n    }\n  } else {\n    ## set explicitly to character(0) in case it was given as NULL\n    by <- character(0)\n  }\n\n  # check that baseline exists\n  comparators <- as.vector(unique(scores[[compare]]))\n  assert_subset(baseline, comparators)\n\n  # check there are enough comparators\n  if (length(setdiff(comparators, baseline)) < 2) {\n    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n    cli_abort(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"More than one non-baseline model is needed to compute\n        pairwise compairisons.\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n  }\n\n  # check that values of the chosen metric are not NA\n  if (anyNA(scores[[metric]])) {\n    scores <- scores[!is.na(scores[[metric]])]\n    if (nrow(scores) == 0) {\n      #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n      cli_abort(\n        c(\n          \"!\" = \"After removing {.val NA} values for {.var {metric}},\n         no values were left.\"\n        )\n      )\n    }\n    cli_warn(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"Some values for the metric {.var {metric}}\n         are NA. These have been removed.\",\n        \"i\" = \"Maybe choose a different metric?\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n  }\n\n  # check that all values of the chosen metric are positive\n  if (any(sign(scores[[metric]]) < 0) && any(sign(scores[[metric]]) > 0)) {\n    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter object_usage_linter\n    cli_abort(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"To compute pairwise comparisons, all values of {.var {metric}}\n       must have the same sign.\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n  }\n\n  # identify unit of single observation.\n  forecast_unit <- get_forecast_unit(scores)\n\n  # if compare is equal to forecast_unit, then pairwise comparisons don't make\n  # sense\n  # if compare == forecast_unit then all relative skill scores will simply be 1.\n  if (setequal(compare, forecast_unit)) {\n    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n    cli_warn(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"`compare` is set to the unit of a single forecast. This doesn't\n            look right.\",\n        \"i\" = \"All relative skill scores will be equal to 1.\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n  } else if (setequal(c(compare, by), forecast_unit)) {\n    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n    cli_inform(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"relative skill can only be computed if the combination of\n        `compare` and `by` is different from the unit of a single forecast.\",\n        \"i\" = \"`by` was set to an empty character vector\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n    by <- character(0)\n  }\n\n  # do the pairwise comparison -------------------------------------------------\n  # split data set into groups determined by 'by'\n  split_scores <- split(scores, by = by)\n\n  results <- lapply(split_scores,\n    FUN = function(scores) {\n      pairwise_comparison_one_group(\n        scores = scores,\n        metric = metric,\n        baseline = baseline,\n        compare = compare,\n        by = by,\n        ...\n      )\n    }\n  )\n\n  out <- data.table::rbindlist(results)\n\n  return(out[])\n}\n\n#' @title Do pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts\n#'\n#' @description\n#' This function does the pairwise comparison for one set of forecasts, but\n#' multiple models involved. It gets called from [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n#' [get_pairwise_comparisons()] splits the data into arbitrary subgroups\n#' specified by the user (e.g. if pairwise comparison should be done separately\n#' for different forecast targets) and then the actual pairwise comparison for\n#' that subgroup is managed from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()]. In order to\n#' actually do the comparison between two models over a subset of common\n#' forecasts it calls [compare_forecasts()].\n#' @inherit get_pairwise_comparisons params return\n#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n#' @importFrom data.table setnames\n#' @keywords internal\n\npairwise_comparison_one_group <- function(scores,\n                                          metric,\n                                          baseline,\n                                          compare = \"model\",\n                                          by,\n                                          ...) {\n  if (!(compare %in% names(scores))) {\n    cli_abort(\n      \"pairwise comparisons require a column as given by `compare`\"\n    )\n  }\n\n  # get list of models\n  comparators <- unique(scores[[compare]])\n\n  # if there aren't enough models to do any comparison, abort\n  if (length(comparators) < 2) {\n    cli_abort(\n      c(\"!\" = \"There are not enough comparators to do any comparison\")\n    )\n  }\n\n  # create a data.frame with results\n  # we only need to do the calculation once, because for the ratio that\n  # should just be the inverse and for the permutation the result should\n  # be the same\n\n  # set up initial data.frame with all possible pairwise comparisons\n  combinations <- data.table::as.data.table(t(combn(comparators, m = 2)))\n  colnames(combinations) <- c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\")\n\n  combinations[, c(\"ratio\", \"pval\") := compare_forecasts(\n    compare = compare,\n    scores = scores,\n    name_comparator1 = ..compare,\n    name_comparator2 = compare_against,\n    metric = metric,\n    ...\n  ),\n  by = seq_len(NROW(combinations))\n  ]\n\n  combinations <- combinations[order(ratio)]\n  combinations[, adj_pval := p.adjust(pval)]\n\n  # mirror computations\n  combinations_mirrored <- data.table::copy(combinations)\n  setnames(combinations_mirrored,\n    old = c(\"..compare\", \"compare_against\"),\n    new = c(\"compare_against\", \"..compare\")\n  )\n  combinations_mirrored[, ratio := 1 / ratio]\n\n  # add a one for those that are the same\n  combinations_equal <- data.table::data.table(\n    ..compare = comparators,\n    compare_against = comparators,\n    ratio = 1,\n    pval = 1,\n    adj_pval = 1\n  )\n  result <- data.table::rbindlist(list(\n    combinations,\n    combinations_mirrored,\n    combinations_equal\n  ),\n  use.names = TRUE\n  )\n\n  # make result character instead of factor\n  result[, `:=`(\n    ..compare = as.character(..compare),\n    compare_against = as.character(compare_against)\n  )]\n\n  setnames(result, old = \"..compare\", new = compare)\n\n  # calculate relative skill as geometric mean\n  # small theta is again better (assuming that the score is negatively oriented)\n  result[, `:=`(\n    theta = geometric_mean(ratio)\n  ),\n  by = compare,\n  ]\n\n  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n    baseline_theta <- unique(result[get(compare) == baseline, ]$theta)\n    if (length(baseline_theta) == 0) {\n      cli_abort(\n        \"Baseline comparator {.var {baseline}} missing.\"\n      )\n    }\n    result[, rel_to_baseline := theta / baseline_theta]\n  }\n\n  # remove all the rows that are not present in by before merging\n  cols_to_keep <- unique(c(by, compare))\n  cols_to_remove <- colnames(scores)[!(colnames(scores) %in% cols_to_keep)]\n  scores[, eval(cols_to_remove) := NULL]\n  scores <- unique(scores)\n  # allow.cartesian needs to be set as sometimes rows will be duplicated a lot\n  out <- merge(scores, result, by = compare, all = TRUE)\n\n  # rename ratio to mean_scores_ratio\n  data.table::setnames(out,\n    old = c(\"ratio\", \"theta\"),\n    new = c(\n      \"mean_scores_ratio\",\n      paste(metric, \"relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n    )\n  )\n  if (!is.null(baseline)) {\n    data.table::setnames(out,\n      old = \"rel_to_baseline\",\n      new = paste(metric, \"scaled_relative_skill\", sep = \"_\")\n    )\n  }\n\n  return(out[])\n}\n\n#' @title Compare a subset of common forecasts\n#'\n#' @description\n#' This function compares two comparators based on the subset of forecasts for which\n#' both comparators have made a prediction. It gets called\n#' from [pairwise_comparison_one_group()], which handles the\n#' comparison of multiple comparators on a single set of forecasts (there are no\n#' subsets of forecasts to be distinguished). [pairwise_comparison_one_group()]\n#' in turn gets called from from [get_pairwise_comparisons()] which can handle\n#' pairwise comparisons for a set of forecasts with multiple subsets, e.g.\n#' pairwise comparisons for one set of forecasts, but done separately for two\n#' different forecast targets.\n#' @inheritParams get_pairwise_comparisons\n#' @param name_comparator1 Character, name of the first comparator\n#' @param name_comparator2 Character, name of the comparator to compare against\n#' @param one_sided Boolean, default is `FALSE`, whether two conduct a one-sided\n#'   instead of a two-sided test to determine significance in a pairwise\n#'   comparison.\n#' @param test_type Character, either \"non_parametric\" (the default), \"permutation\",\n#'   or NULL. This determines which kind of test shall be conducted to determine\n#'   p-values. If NULL, no test will be conducted and p-values will be NA.\n#' @param n_permutations Numeric, the number of permutations for a\n#'   permutation test. Default is 999.\n#' @returns A list with mean score ratios and p-values for the comparison\n#' between two comparators\n#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n#' @author Johannes Bracher, \\email{johannes.bracher@@kit.edu}\n#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n#' @keywords internal\n\ncompare_forecasts <- function(scores,\n                              compare = \"model\",\n                              name_comparator1,\n                              name_comparator2,\n                              metric,\n                              one_sided = FALSE,\n                              test_type = c(\"non_parametric\", \"permutation\", NULL),\n                              n_permutations = 999) {\n  scores <- data.table::as.data.table(scores)\n\n  forecast_unit <- get_forecast_unit(scores)\n\n  if (!(compare %in% names(scores))) {\n    cli_abort(\n      \"pairwise comparisons require a column as given by `compare`\"\n    )\n  }\n\n  # select only columns in c(by, var)\n  a <- scores[get(compare) == name_comparator1]\n  b <- scores[get(compare) == name_comparator2]\n\n  # remove compare column from 'by' before merging\n  merge_by <- setdiff(forecast_unit, compare)\n\n  overlap <- merge(a, b, by = merge_by, allow.cartesian = TRUE)\n  overlap <- unique(overlap)\n\n  if (nrow(overlap) == 0) {\n    return(list(ratio = NA_real_, pval = NA_real_))\n  }\n\n  values_x <- overlap[[paste0(metric, \".x\")]]\n  values_y <- overlap[[paste0(metric, \".y\")]]\n\n  # calculate ratio to of average scores achieved by both comparator.\n  # this should be equivalent to theta_ij in Johannes Bracher's document.\n  # ratio < 1 --> comparator 1 is better.\n  # note we could also take mean(values_x) / mean(values_y), as it cancels out\n  ratio <- sum(values_x) / sum(values_y)\n\n  # If test_type is NULL, return NA for p-value\n  if (is.null(test_type)) {\n    pval <- NA_real_\n  } else {\n    # test whether the ratio is significantly different from one\n    # equivalently, one can test whether the difference between the two values\n    # is significantly different from zero.\n    test_type <- match.arg(test_type)\n    if (test_type == \"permutation\") {\n      # adapted from the surveillance package\n      pval <- permutation_test(values_x, values_y,\n        n_permutation = n_permutations,\n        one_sided = one_sided,\n        comparison_mode = \"difference\"\n      )\n    } else {\n      # this probably needs some more thought\n      # alternative: do a paired t-test on ranks?\n      pval <- wilcox.test(values_x, values_y, paired = TRUE)$p.value\n    }\n  }\n\n  return(list(\n    mean_scores_ratio = ratio,\n    pval = pval\n  ))\n}\n\n\n#' @title Calculate geometric mean\n#'\n#' @details\n#' Used in [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n#'\n#' @param x Numeric vector of values for which to calculate the geometric mean.\n#' @returns The geometric mean of the values in `x`. `NA` values are ignored.\n#'\n#' @keywords internal\ngeometric_mean <- function(x) {\n  geometric_mean <- exp(mean(log(x[!is.na(x)])))\n  return(geometric_mean)\n}\n\n#' @title Simple permutation test\n#'\n#' @description\n#' The implementation of the permutation test follows the\n#' function\n#' `permutationTest` from the `surveillance` package by Michael Höhle,\n#' Andrea Riebler and Michaela Paul.\n#' The function compares two vectors of scores. It computes the mean of each\n#' vector independently and then takes either the difference or the ratio of\n#' the two. This observed difference or ratio is compared against the same\n#' test statistic based on permutations of the original data.\n#'\n#' Used in [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n#'\n#' @param scores1 Vector of scores to compare against another vector of scores.\n#' @param scores2 A second vector of scores to compare against the first\n#' @param n_permutation The number of replications to use for a permutation\n#' test. More replications yield more exact results, but require more\n#' computation.\n#' @param one_sided Whether or not to compute a one-sided test. Default is\n#'   `FALSE`.\n#' @param comparison_mode How to compute the test statistic for the comparison\n#'   of the two scores. Should be either \"difference\" or \"ratio\".\n#'\n#' @returns p-value of the permutation test\n#' @keywords internal\npermutation_test <- function(scores1,\n                             scores2,\n                             n_permutation = 999,\n                             one_sided = FALSE,\n                             comparison_mode = c(\"difference\", \"ratio\")) {\n  nTime <- length(scores1)\n  meanscores1 <- mean(scores1)\n  meanscores2 <- mean(scores2)\n  comparison_mode <- match.arg(comparison_mode)\n  if (comparison_mode == \"ratio\") {\n    # distinguish between on-sided and two-sided:\n    test_stat_observed <- ifelse(\n      one_sided,\n      meanscores1 / meanscores2,\n      max(meanscores1 / meanscores2, meanscores2 / meanscores1)\n    )\n  } else {\n    test_stat_observed <- ifelse(\n      one_sided,\n      meanscores1 - meanscores2,\n      abs(meanscores1 - meanscores2)\n    )\n  }\n  test_stat_permuted <- replicate(n_permutation, {\n    sel <- rbinom(nTime, size = 1, prob = 0.5)\n    g1 <- (sum(scores1[sel == 0]) + sum(scores2[sel == 1])) / nTime\n    g2 <- (sum(scores1[sel == 1]) + sum(scores2[sel == 0])) / nTime\n    if (comparison_mode == \"ratio\") {\n      ifelse(one_sided, g1 / g2, max(g1 / g2, g2 / g1))\n    } else {\n      ifelse(one_sided, g1 - g2, abs(g1 - g2))\n    }\n  })\n  pVal <- (1 + sum(test_stat_permuted >= test_stat_observed)) / (n_permutation + 1)\n  # plus ones to make sure p-val is never 0?\n  return(pVal)\n}\n\n\n#' Add relative skill scores based on pairwise comparisons\n#'\n#' Adds a columns with relative skills computed by running\n#' pairwise comparisons on the scores.\n#' For more information on\n#' the computation of relative skill, see [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n#' Relative skill will be calculated for the aggregation level specified in\n#' `by`.\n#'\n#' @inheritParams get_pairwise_comparisons\n#' @export\n#' @keywords scoring\nadd_relative_skill <- function(\n  scores,\n  compare = \"model\",\n  by = NULL,\n  metric = intersect(c(\"wis\", \"crps\", \"brier_score\"), names(scores)),\n  baseline = NULL,\n  ...\n) {\n\n  # input checks are done in `get_pairwise_comparisons()`\n  # do pairwise comparisons ----------------------------------------------------\n  pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(\n    scores = scores,\n    metric = metric,\n    baseline = baseline,\n    compare = compare,\n    by = by,\n    ...\n  )\n\n  # store original metrics\n  metrics <- get_metrics.scores(scores)\n\n  # delete unnecessary columns\n  pairwise[, c(\n    \"compare_against\", \"mean_scores_ratio\",\n    \"pval\", \"adj_pval\"\n  ) := NULL]\n  pairwise <- unique(pairwise)\n\n  # merge back\n  scores <- merge(\n    scores, pairwise, all.x = TRUE, by = get_forecast_unit(pairwise)\n  )\n\n  # Update score names\n  new_metrics <- paste(\n    metric, c(\"relative_skill\", \"scaled_relative_skill\"),\n    sep = \"_\"\n  )\n  new_metrics <- new_metrics[new_metrics %in% names(scores)]\n  scores <- new_scores(scores, metrics = c(metrics, new_metrics))\n\n  return(scores)\n}\n\n\n#' @title Plot heatmap of pairwise comparisons\n#'\n#' @description\n#' Creates a heatmap of the ratios or pvalues from a pairwise comparison\n#' between models.\n#'\n#' @param comparison_result A data.frame as produced by\n#' [get_pairwise_comparisons()].\n#' @param type Character vector of length one that is either\n#'   \"mean_scores_ratio\" or \"pval\". This denotes whether to\n#'   visualise the ratio or the p-value of the pairwise comparison.\n#'   Default is \"mean_scores_ratio\".\n#' @importFrom ggplot2 ggplot aes geom_tile geom_text labs coord_cartesian\n#'   scale_fill_gradient2 theme_light element_text\n#' @importFrom data.table as.data.table setnames rbindlist\n#' @importFrom stats reorder\n#' @importFrom ggplot2 labs coord_cartesian facet_wrap facet_grid theme\n#'   element_text element_blank\n#' @return\n#' A ggplot object with a heatmap of mean score ratios from pairwise\n#' comparisons.\n#' @export\n#' @examples\n#' library(ggplot2)\n#' scores <- example_quantile |>\n#'   as_forecast_quantile() |>\n#'   score()\n#' pairwise <- get_pairwise_comparisons(scores, by = \"target_type\")\n#' plot_pairwise_comparisons(pairwise, type = \"mean_scores_ratio\") +\n#'   facet_wrap(~target_type)\n\nplot_pairwise_comparisons <- function(comparison_result,\n                                      type = c(\"mean_scores_ratio\", \"pval\")) {\n  comparison_result <- ensure_data.table(comparison_result)\n  type <- match.arg(type)\n\n  relative_skill_metric <- grep(\n    \"(?<!scaled)_relative_skill$\", colnames(comparison_result),\n    value = TRUE, perl = TRUE\n  )\n  comparison_result[, model := reorder(model, -get(relative_skill_metric))]\n  levels <- levels(comparison_result$model)\n\n  get_fill_scale <- function(values, breaks, plot_scales) {\n    values[is.na(values)] <- 1 # this would be either ratio = 1 or pval = 1\n    scale <- cut(\n      values,\n      breaks = breaks,\n      include.lowest = TRUE,\n      right = FALSE,\n      labels = plot_scales\n    )\n    return(as.numeric(as.character(scale)))\n  }\n\n  type <- match.arg(type)\n\n  if (type == \"mean_scores_ratio\") {\n    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := round(mean_scores_ratio, 2)]\n\n    # implement breaks for colour heatmap\n    breaks <- c(0, 0.1, 0.5, 0.75, 1, 1.33, 2, 10, Inf)\n    plot_scales <- c(-1, -0.5, -0.25, 0, 0, 0.25, 0.5, 1)\n    comparison_result[, fill_col := get_fill_scale(\n      var_of_interest,\n      breaks, plot_scales\n    )]\n\n    high_col <- \"salmon\"\n  } else if (type == \"pval\") {\n    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := round(pval, 3)]\n    # implemnt breaks for colour heatmap\n    breaks <- c(0, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1)\n    plot_scales <- c(1, 0.5, 0.1, 0)\n    comparison_result[, fill_col := get_fill_scale(\n      var_of_interest,\n      breaks, plot_scales\n    )]\n\n    high_col <- \"palegreen3\"\n    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := as.character(var_of_interest)]\n    comparison_result[, var_of_interest := ifelse(var_of_interest == \"0\",\n                                                  \"< 0.001\", var_of_interest)]\n  }\n\n  plot <- ggplot(\n    comparison_result,\n    aes(\n      y = reorder(model, 1 / mean_scores_ratio, FUN = geometric_mean),\n      x = reorder(compare_against, mean_scores_ratio, FUN = geometric_mean),\n      fill = fill_col\n    )\n  ) +\n    geom_tile(\n      color = \"white\",\n      width = 0.97, height = 0.97\n    ) +\n    geom_text(aes(label = var_of_interest),\n              na.rm = TRUE) +\n    scale_fill_gradient2(\n      low = \"steelblue\", mid = \"grey95\",\n      high = high_col,\n      na.value = \"lightgrey\",\n      midpoint = 0,\n      limits = c(-1, 1),\n      name = NULL\n    ) +\n    theme_scoringutils() +\n    theme(\n      axis.text.x = element_text(\n        angle = 90, vjust = 1,\n        hjust = 1\n      ),\n      legend.position = \"none\"\n    ) +\n    labs(\n      x = \"\", y = \"\"\n    ) +\n    coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE)\n  if (type == \"mean_scores_ratio\") {\n    plot <- plot +\n      theme(\n        axis.text.x = element_text(\n          angle = 90, vjust = 1,\n          hjust = 1, color = \"brown4\"\n        ),\n        axis.text.y = element_text(color = \"steelblue4\")\n      )\n  }\n\n  return(plot)\n}\n","numLines":764,"startLine":1,"totalLines":764}}}
